title: For Sale/Trade:  Finnish M27 *Must See*
postcontent: Up for sale is a beautiful example of a very rare gun. That is correct, this is a true Finnish Mosin M27 chambered in 7.62x54R. This is not the more common M39 or M91. Gun is in great condition considering its age and possible history. This is a Tikka rifle dated 1932. Bolt has the correct "wings" that correspond with the hex receiver for tight lockup and a great trigger. Numbers match on this rifle. Also has the correct 27" heavy barrel associated with these guns complete with original cleaning rod. Bore is a little dark but the lands are still very sharp and crisp. Only real issue is a small gouge above the trigger on the stock which appears to have occured some time ago. If you know your history and your Mosins, you know this is a true collectors piece. postcontent: The TASER M26C uses replaceable cartridges which have 2 - 15' wires coiled inside, each with a sharp barb on the end. Once fired, the barbs, or electrodes, are launched up to 15 feet towards your subject. The barbs can penetrate up to 1" thick of clothing. Once penetrated, either clothing or skin, the wires deliver the electric current to the subject. While the voltage and amperage of a TASER Gun are lower than those of direct contact stun guns, the current is much more effective. This is because TASER uses their patented Neuro-Muscular Incapacitation technology in their electrical current. What this means is that the current the TASER Gun generates mimics that of the human body. So, once the electrical current is delivered into the human body, the body's brain and central nervous system cannot discern what's going on and "freaks out". The brain and nervous system doesn't know what to do. Further, the M26C can also be used as a direct contact stun gun in a close encounter situation. Also this rifle has the correct WWII front sight hood and not some cheap repro. The receiver code is 4022 which matches the barrel, trigger, trigger guard, magazine floor plate, rear sight ramp, rear sight leaf, rear sight slide, and magazine follower. The bolt is Steyr coded WaA623 and completely matches itself with all parts coded 4420 which is pretty close to the receiver code. The stock is also stamped WaA623 and is a beautiful specimen and also has an unusual bonus of having a large M stamped below the takedown disk which indicates that it was used by the Kreigsmarine or the German Navy. Most K98 stocks have the H stamp for the heer or Army. The M stamped stocks are rare. The stock serial number is 2260 which matches the front and rear bands, band spring, and bayonet lug. All of these parts are also stamped WaA77 or WaA623. Overall, this is a beautiful all time period rifle and would make a great addition to any collection. title: For Sale/Trade:  Bushmaster ACR 14.5" Barrel EOtech w/Magnifier
postcontent:
Less than 500 rounds down the pipe Bushmaster ACR. It has a 14.5" barrel that was professionally cut, crowned and had a Noveske Flaming Pig muzzle device pinned and welded.  MoA is still 1.5, and has an insanely low amount of recoil allowing for lightning fast follow up shots. The sights hardly leave the target.  Included in the price is both an EO Tech 512 ($400) and EO Tech G33 Magnifier ($600). Also included are the Magpul back up iron sights, 3 MOE rail sections and attached GG&G vertical grip.  It is the folding stock variant and has the standard handguard.  Great rifle, possibly the best 5.56mm platform on the market in terms of reliability, ergonomics, stability and accuracy.  Takes standard M4/AR15 Stanag mags.  I simply need the money to finish other projects.  EO Teck 512 and G33 are genuine and will come with original cases and paperwork.

*Read below knowing the first time you fire it and use 5.56mm ammo like the caliber in the add clearly states, and you have a single issue. Call me and I will gladly take the rifle back and give you a refund. I stand behind what I say below entirely. 

*Full disclosure, it does not like to cycle wolf ammo after the barrel has been cut. I did not adjust the gas system or recoil spring after I had the barrel modified so weak .223 loads can cause a failure to feed due to the fact there is not as much gas coming back into the gun as with the 16" barrel and cheaper .223 rounds are made with the bare minimum powder to cycle the weapons system.  Federal, Winchester and other brands of brass cased .223 cycle flawlessly.  Any and all 5.56mm cycles without issue as well.  Bottom line, buy good ammo, have 0 problems.  If it is of major concern to you, note that the recoil spring will eventually be broken in through firing and you will be able to fire weaker loads. Also you can easily fix this problem by "conditioning' the recoil spring by leaving the bolt locked to the rear for long periods of time, enlarging the gas port, or by taking 1 or 2 links out of the recoil spring (Please do not attempt the last two unless you know EXACTLY what you are doing).  So, I just have directed my energies elsewhere and have not done this yet. Mainly by being deployed overseas. lol Rest assured, as soon as I do fix these issues and test the rifle, this message will come down and the price will go up.  Thank you for your consideration.
